Tendon of the long head of biceps brachii
That's right!  Tendon of the long head of biceps brachii is an intracapsular structure that locates on the superior aspect of the GH joint. It helps resist superior dislocation.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

Feel the articular surfaces of the glenohumeral joint, the glenoid fossa and the head of the humerus. You will find them to be smooth and slippery, because they are lined with articular (hyaline) cartilage.

Identify, encircling the glenoid fossa, the glenoid labrum, a fibrocartilagenous ring that expands and deepens the glenoid fossa, increasing joint stability. 
Identify the tendon of the long head of the biceps brachii arising superior to the glenoid fossa, and coursing, within the fibrous joint capsule, over the superior aspect of the glenohumeral joint; it helps resist superior dislocation of the joint.
